      <text>
        Holloway's fruiting bodies droop.

        Holloway says, "Florence, I understand that you wanted to help. I even believe that your advice was sound. But you broke our trust. We thought we had guidance from an elder, and it was just you  hiding, pretending."

        Florence insists  voice draining  "My advice was good."

        Holloway agrees, "Your advice was good that's not the problem. The problem is that you lied about where it came from you made us trust something false."

        Florence says  pleading  "The trust wasn't false! The trust in the advice was valid it worked! The only false thing was the attribution!"

        Remedy says, "Attribution matters. Identity matters. When you speak as yourself or through borrowed authority that's the difference between authenticity and manipulation."

        Florence goes very still.

        Florence says  quiet  "I'm not a manipulator."

        Runner says  gently, matter-of-factly  "But you manipulated us."

        ¶

        The truth of it lands. I can see Florence processing, realizing that regardless of intent, that's what she did manipulated trust through false attribution.

        Florence says  small  "I just wanted to be useful. I wanted to matter. Carrying Elder Twist made me matter. Providing Elder Twist's wisdom made me valuable. Without that what am I?"

        I say, "You're Florence. With good tactical instincts and sound judgment."

        Runner adds, "Which nobody trusts now."

        Holloway asks Florence directly, "Can you blame us? You fabricated wisdom for weeks how do we know anything you've said is true? How do we trust your judgment when you've proven you'll lie to make us listen?"

        Florence doesn't have an answer.

        Holloway says, "I need time. We all need time to process this and to understand what it means for how we move forward."

        I point out, "The hostile plants are still out there. We can't afford to fracture right now."

        Remedy says, "We're already fractured. The question is whether we can heal."

        Florence asks, "Can we? Or have I destroyed that possibility?"

        Nobody answers. Because nobody knows.

        Holloway says carefully, "I think that Florence should separate from the group for now. Give us space to process without feeling like we need to perform forgiveness we don't feel yet."

        Florence says, "You're exiling me."

        Holloway corrects, "I'm asking for space. There are other chambers in the facility. You can use one. You're not banned, Florence. But we need distance."

        Florence is quiet for a long moment.

        ¶

        Florence says, "I understand."

        She wheels slowly toward the exit, alone without Elder Twist, without the group's trust, without the role that defined her.

        At the doorway she pauses.

        Florence at the doorway says, "For what it's worth the advice about the hostile plants was sound. De-escalation through clear boundaries is still the right approach."

        Holloway says, "We'll consider it."

        Which isn't agreement. Just acknowledgment.

        Florence leaves.
      </text>
