        The room feels smaller without her, and somehow heavier — the weight of betrayal takes up more space than a plant ever could.

        Remedy says eventually — "That was awful."

        Holloway agrees — "Yes."

        I say quietly — "She was right, though — about the advice being good, about you probably not valuing it if it came from her directly."

        Runner says — "That doesn't excuse the lying."

        I reply — "No. But it explains it."

        Holloway says tiredly — "Explanation isn't justification — Florence had good reasons for what she did; that doesn't make it right."

        Scout presses harder against my leg — they're confused — they understand betrayal but not the nuance, can't parse the layers of Florence being both wrong and wronged.

        Velvet asks — "What do we do now?"

        Holloway admits — "I don't know — we have hostile plants threatening our boundary — internal trust broken — Florence's advice, which might be good but comes from someone we can't trust — and we have…"

        ¶

        Holloway finishes — "all of this."

        Runner suggests — "We handle the immediate threat first — then we figure out how to rebuild trust."

        Remedy asks — "In what order?"

        Remedy continues — "Because Florence's advice about de-escalation might be our best response to the hostile plants, but using her guidance after this feels…"

        I supply — "Hypocritical?"

        Remedy finishes — "Complicated."

        I say — "Yeah — complicated covers it."

        We talk for another hour but don't reach conclusions — just more complexity, more questions, more uncertainty about how to move forward.

        Eventually we disperse and Scout and I return to my room, but sleep doesn't come easily.

        Somewhere in the facility, Florence is alone with her good judgment that nobody trusts anymore.

        Outside, hostile plants are organizing while nobody's quite sure how to respond.

        We needed to be _stronger_ — more _unified_.

        Instead we're fractured, uncertain, and facing threats from both outside and within.

        Florence was right about one thing — her advice probably was sound.

        But that might not matter anymore.
      </text>
